# Third-Party Notices

This file enumerates third-party software that the `tac` (Task-Aware Codec) project
depends on at runtime, build time, or via reference. The project itself is licensed
under the MIT License — see `LICENSE` at the repository root.

The project's MIT posture (and this comprehensive notices file) is aligned with
comma.ai's canonical OSS posture across `commaai/openpilot`,
`commaai/comma_video_compression_challenge`, and `tinygrad/tinygrad` — all of
which use MIT exclusively, no Apache 2.0, no copyleft, no CLA. comma.ai itself
does not maintain a root-level `THIRD_PARTY_NOTICES.md`; this project chooses the
more comprehensive path because the dep set evolves rapidly during the
research-stage and explicit notices are easier to audit than tracing each
pip-installed package's internal LICENSE. See
`reports/oss_d3_d4_drafts_20260514/comma_ai_alignment_addendum.md` for the
full posture-alignment rationale.

Per project policy, all runtime dependencies must be under permissive licenses
compatible with MIT redistribution (MIT, Apache-2.0, BSD-2/3-Clause, HPND, MPL-2.0,
ISC, PSF, Python-2.0, BSL-1.0). Copyleft licenses (GPL family, LGPL when
statically linked, AGPL) are not accepted as runtime deps without explicit
operator review and an isolation plan. The single documented exception is
`pyppmd` (LGPL-2.1-or-later, dynamically-linked PyPI dep), which is
precedent-matched to the upstream contest `pyproject.toml`
(`commaai/comma_video_compression_challenge`).

The list below is non-vendored: we do not include third-party source code in this
repository (other than the pinned upstream challenge snapshot under `upstream/`,
which is governed by its own license — see "Pinned upstream snapshot" below).
Dependencies are installed via `pip` / `uv` from PyPI at install time. Each
listing below records the package name, version range pinned by
`pyproject.toml` (or, where applicable, the Modal worker image at
`experiments/modal_train_lane.py:60-83`), the upstream license, and the upstream
project home.

